		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://bestsellerlabs.com/?p=21175</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Guest post by Marcy McKay, award-winning copy-writer, novelist, short-story author and freelance journalist. - Every writer has experienced this emotion. When ‘it’ happens, your head explodes, rage swirls through you, while an imaginary fist pounds your gut. When? Why? It so happens that overnight, the internet has been buzzing with the latest literary whiz kid, who hit the New [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="font-size: large;"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-21258" alt="Jealousy" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/jealousy-shutterstock-600-green.jpg" width="600" height="400" /></span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: left; padding-left: 30px;"><span style="font-size: small; color: #464646;"><em><strong>Guest post</strong> by Marcy McKay, award-winning copy-writer, novelist, short-story author and freelance journalist.<br />
<span style="font-size: xx-small; color: #ffffff;">-</span></em></span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="font-size: large;"><span style="font-size: x-large;">E</span></span></span><strong><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">very writer has experienced this emotion. When ‘it’ happens, your head explodes, rage swirls through you, while an imaginary fist pounds your gut.</span></strong></p>
<p><strong>When? Why?</strong></p>
<p>It so happens that overnight, the internet has been buzzing with the latest literary whiz kid, who hit the New York Times Bestsellers List.<em> </em></p>
<p><em>“It was my first try at a novel,”</em> she chirps.</p>
<p>Your bitterness tastes like bile.  Rage and resentment flood your veins.  That poison you’re feeling is…</p>
<p><strong>Jealousy</strong></p>
<p><span id="more-21175"></span></p>
<p>No matter how the scenario plays out, the end result is the same.  You hate another writer for having what you want: fame, fortune and fabulousness.  All that glory should be yours.</p>
<p>This emotion is so all-consuming that its evil twin – envy, is listed as one of the Seven Deadly Sins.  The desire for others’ traits, status, abilities or situation is such an offense here in the human realm that your punishment is to spend eternity in the freezing waters of Hell.</p>
<p>I didn’t even know that Hell had freezing waters, but I’d rather not find out.</p>
<p><strong>Jealous Much?</strong></p>
<p>Jealousy does not work and play well with others.  There’s no room for abundance.  Only you get to be king of the mountain.</p>
<p>This recent <a href="http://www.salon.com/2014/09/15/my_ugly_inner_battle_how_jealousy_poisoned_my_friendship_with_john_green/" target="_blank">Salon article</a> showcases how one author’s deep envy for John Green on his success with <strong>&#8220;The Fault in Our Stars&#8221;</strong> almost destroyed their friendship.</p>
<blockquote><p>Nathan Rabin admits&#8230;</p>
<p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-21192" alt="The Fault in Our Stars" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/The_Fault_in_Our_Stars150.jpg" width="150" height="220" /><em>“I did not like the way it (jealousy) made me feel resentful, petty, insignificant and small. I hated the way it made me feel grubby and desperate, opportunistic and scheming. </em></p>
<p><em>My spirit, if you will, was gracious and happy for John, but my ego, the infernal ego, cried out, “Why not me? Haven’t I paid my dues? Haven’t I written lots of books? Why can’t I be even a fraction that successful?”</em></p></blockquote>
<p><strong>Jealousy is a Disease</strong></p>
<p>Get well soon.</p>
<p>Jealousy is hard enough to deal with, but when you rip off its mask, you’ll discover the true culprit is that rat-bastard – fear.  Fear another writer has what you want… fear you won’t get the success you deserve… fear they are stealing what is rightfully yours, even if you’re not putting in the time and energy to make it happen.</p>
<p>Fear has just one job – to stop you from writing.  What better way to avoid getting published than to stew in your own righteous indignation?</p>
<blockquote><p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-21195" alt="The Artists Way" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/artistsway150.jpg" width="150" height="180" />In <strong>&#8220;The Artist’s Way&#8221;</strong>, Julia Cameron says,</p>
<p>“Jealousy is a stingy emotion. It produces tunnel vision.  <span style="line-height: 1.5em;">It narrows our ability to see things in perspective…the biggest lie that jealousy tells us is that we have no choice but to be jealous.”</span></p></blockquote>
<p>This intense emotion holds you hostage.  <span style="line-height: 1.5em;">So paralyzed with rage, you can’t see that taking action is what will save you.  A</span><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">ction will set you free. </span></p>
<p><strong><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Let Jealousy Be Your Guide</span></strong></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Jealousy is a map, according to Cameron. If you listen, it will tell you exactly where you need to go.  Let jealousy be your guide.  </span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>How to Make A Jealousy Map:</strong></p>
<p>Make three columns:</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Column #1</strong> lists WHO you envy.<br />
<strong>Column #2</strong> lists WHY you’re jealous of them – be as specific as you can to best understand your rage.<br />
<strong>Column #3</strong> lists your ACTION to take to free you from jealousy and lead to creative success.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><span style="color: #808080;">Example&#8230;</span></em></p>
<p><strong style="line-height: 1.5em;"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-21237" alt="jealousy-map" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/jealousy-map-s.jpg" width="600" height="347" /></strong></p>
<p><strong style="line-height: 1.5em;">Big Change Starts With Small Steps</strong></p>
<p>In fact, the tinier the action the better, or the creative risk might terrify you and freeze you to the spot (like those freezing waters in Hell).</p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">I love this quote by Cameron. </span><em style="line-height: 1.5em;">“Green is the color of jealousy, but it’s also the color of hope.” </em><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Use that forceful energy to lead your writing to a better place, because the opportunity for writers has never been greater. </span></p>
<p>You have more choices than ever before.  Traditional publishing, do-it-yourself, or a hybrid combination of both.  Social media provides endless ways to build a platform and create loyal, passionate followers.  <span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Blogs such as Bestseller Labs provide writers with the blueprint for success.</span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Let your green-eyed monster make you insanely successful, rather than just insane.</span></p>
<p><em><strong style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><br />
</span></strong></em><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-21185" alt="macy-and-book2" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/macy-and-book2.jpg" width="250" height="188" /><em><strong style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">This is a guest post by Marcy McKay, who is the Energizer Bunny of Writers</span></strong></em></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">She believes writing is delicious and messy and hard and important. </span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">If you’ve ever struggled with your writing, you can download her new, FREE eBook, </span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><a href="http://mudpiewriting.com/landing/struggling-with-your-writing/" target="_blank">Writing Naked: One Writer Dares to Bare All</a>  </span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: xx-small; color: #ffffff;">-</span><strong style="color: #c23d40; line-height: 1.5em;"><br />
How do you handle jealousy? What do you think about using your jealousy to lead to greater success?   Please do leave a comment.<br />
</strong><span style="color: #ffffff; font-size: xx-small;">-</span></p>
