		<title>10 Key Questions That Can Determine Your Success As A Writer</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/BestsellerLabs/~3/Fc_tkLWzfUo/</link>
		<comments>http://bestsellerlabs.com/10-questions-that-determine-success/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 26 Jun 2014 04:17:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jonathan Gunson]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Book Marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Creativity & Inspiration]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Writing Tips]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[advice to writers]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[author tips]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[book advertising]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[book marketing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[how to have a bestseller]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[how to write a novel]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Imagination]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[writing tips]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://bestsellerlabs.com/?p=20588</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[There are many powerful ways to significantly improve your chances of building a large book readership.   To help determine the likelihood of you succeeding, I’ve put together ten key questions for you to think about when starting a new writing project.    Prepare to be &#8220;caught in the headlights&#8221; by these questions &#8211; they&#8217;re [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="font-size: x-large;"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-20612" alt="header-books" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/header-books-inferno.jpg" width="600" height="400" />T</span><strong>here are many powerful ways to significantly improve your chances of building a large book readership.  </strong> </span></span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">To help determine the likelihood of you succeeding, </span><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">I’ve put together ten key questions for you to think about when starting a new writing project.   </span></span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Prepare to be &#8220;caught in the headlights&#8221; by these questions &#8211; they&#8217;re designed to expose the reality of being an author, but also to give a useful insight into your career pathway.  </span></span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">In truth, this is not a <em>definitive</em> list, but I&#8217;ve found these particular questions to be helpful guidance in my own work.  Let me know in the comments which of these is relevant to you &#8211; I&#8217;d value the feedback.</span></span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><span id="more-20588"></span></span></span></p>
<h3>1. Do you employ the potency of your TRUE self?</h3>
<p>The most effective way to attract a large and committed readership is to develop your own unique &#8220;Writer’s Voice&#8221;.</p>
<p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-12734" alt="Viral Word of Mouth" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/boygirlbook-s.jpg" width="200" height="133" /></p>
<p>T<span style="line-height: 1.5em;">his requires reaching into your deepest emotional wells, and writing about what you genuinely love &#8211; the things you obsess over.  </span></p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">You need to invoke the potent uniqueness of </span><em style="line-height: 1.5em;">you</em><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">.</span></p>
<p>A unique voice gives you control of a market, because committed reader fans can only ever buy this particular magic from you.  You alone.  Think about the gravity of this.</p>
<p>More about the power of <a href="http://bestsellerlabs.com/the-key-to-growing-readership/ ">“Writer’s Voice”</a> here.</p>
<h3>2. Are you writing for a particular genre because it’s popular?</h3>
<p>Do you write for a particular genre because you believe there’s money in it? That is a sure fire recipe for ending up in nowhere land.  Fortunately there’s a better pathway to your <em>publishing Nirvana</em>.</p>
<p>To quote <a href="http://bestsellerlabs.com/game-of-thrones-editor-reveals-top-writing-tips/"><em>Game Of Thrones</em> editor Jane Johnson</a>:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-6158" alt="Jane Johnson" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/janeshad.jpg" width="110" height="170" />“Write with a fire in your heart… There may be all sorts of received wisdom out there about ‘what agents are looking for’ or ‘what publishers want’ or ‘what’s selling’ but who wants a second-rate copy of someone else’s idea?</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>Write something unique to you and it will stand out from the crowd. Otherwise it’ll be second rate copy of someone else’s work.”</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>Jane Johnson</em></p>
<h3>3. Do you stick to a schedule? (Be honest.)</h3>
<p>When asked for the secret of writing, Irish novelist Maeve Binchy pointed out that in life there are many secrets, such as the secret to having a svelte, flawless body.</p>
<p><span style="line-height: 1.5em;"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-20627" alt="Calendar" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/calendar2.jpg" width="238" height="249" />Unfortunately that particular secret turns out to require endless hours of exercise, dieting, cleansing and nourishing – otherwise known as </span><em style="line-height: 1.5em;">work</em><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">.</span></p>
<p>Her <a href="http://bestsellerlabs.com/maeve-binchy-her-writing-secrets-interview/">&#8220;Secret to Writing&#8221;</a> is not dissimilar.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>&#8220;Set yourself down and do not stand up until you have 5 pages written, and then do that again another day of the week, and if you do 10 pages a week, by year&#8217;s end you’ll have 520 pages… a novel.&#8221;   </em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><em>Maeve Binchy</em></p>
<h3>4. Are you afraid of being judged?</h3>
<p>Have you suffered one of those moments when you completely freeze up and cannot write&#8230; AT ALL?</p>
<p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-20630" alt="fear-of-judgement" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/fear-of-judgement2.jpg" width="238" height="204" /></p>
<p>The most common cause is the fear of being judged.</p>
<p><em>&#8220;What on earth will people think of my book?&#8221;</em> you lament, secretly.  You are not alone.  Hemingway suffered from this to an extreme degree with the huge weight of expectations weighing him down.</p>
<p>How to escape this?  My <a href="http://bestsellerlabs.com/how-to-beat-writers-block-forever/ ">blog post on Writer’s Block</a> shows you how to break free of this syndrome and write freely and creatively.</p>
<h3>5. Do you edit as you write?</h3>
<p>The truth is that writers often edit as they go as a form of procrastination.  (This may be you!)</p>
<p>The bottom line is that editing on the fly will in most cases chloroform creative flow and generate dull writing.  Instead it’s best to slam down all your ideas, with or without a plan, then go back and do the road mending and altering later.</p>
<p>Just get that crap out there!</p>
<h3><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-20633" alt="Editors" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/editors.jpg" width="238" height="171" />6. Do you use a professional editor?</h3>
<p>There’s no other way of saying it:</p>
<p>Typos, verbosity, rodomontade, grandiosity and plain old bad syntax will throw a reader out of the narrative in an instant.</p>
<p>Editors are Gods.<br />
<span style="line-height: 1.5em;">Do employ a good editor. </span></p>
<h3>7. Do you write for a specific, easily identifiable genre?</h3>
<p>e.g. &#8220;Romantic Suspense&#8221;, &#8220;Police Procedural&#8221; &#8220;Mystery Thriller&#8221;, &#8220;Historical Romance.&#8221;</p>
<p>There&#8217;s no question that it’s crucial to write in a way that comes the most easily and naturally to you.  The writing can then flow and produce the magic you seek.</p>
<p>But it’s also true that when a book is written in a clearly identifiable genre it will increase its chances of being discovered by book buyers.</p>
<p>I’m not suggesting that you shoehorn your writing into a genre just so it will be found. Instead it’s a case of being able to clearly identify exactly what it is you’re writing when describing it in the marketplace.</p>
<h3>8. Are you hoping for a bestseller with your first book?</h3>
<p>The reality is that a single book has a very low chance of &#8220;breaking out&#8221;.</p>
<p>By contrast a whole line of books will sell each other, and develop the author’s reputation. It also pays to be aware that a <em>series</em> will generally do even better than simply a collection of novels.  e.g. Harry Potter, Game of Thrones,  A Series Of Unfortunate Events.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="size-full wp-image-697 aligncenter" alt="Series Of Unfortunate Events" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/seriesunfortunate-s1.jpg" width="500" height="249" /></p>
<p>More on the power of series <a href="http://bestsellerlabs.com/the-hottest-tip-no-fiction-writer-can-afford-to-ignore/">in this post:  &#8220;Series&#8221;</a></p>
<h3>9. Are you planning to just write and leave everything else to a publisher?</h3>
<p>Your job is to write, theirs is to publish and promote. Correct?</p>
<p><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-14579" alt="Publishing Contract" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/contract.jpg" width="190" height="126" />I’m sorry to be the bearer of bad tidings. But while that may have been the case, to a certain extent, up to about 30 years ago, publishers now rarely promote books by new authors.</p>
<p>Traditional publishers will only spend money promoting brand name authors such as Nora Roberts or George R.R. Martin, because their large fan bases make them a safe bet.</p>
<p>But if you’re a new author, no such luck, except in rare instances. Even if you do have a publisher it’s still largely down to you to market your own books.</p>
<p>Here are <a href="http://bestsellerlabs.com/7-bestseller-strategies-for-writers/">seven key marketing strategies</a> that will help you to do this successfully.</p>
<h3>10. Do you know WHY you are writing?</h3>
<p>Get clear why you are doing this.</p>
<p>There’s no doubt you’d like to earn some money from your work, but essentially it is <span style="text-decoration: underline;">vocational</span>.</p>
<p>Being a writer embodies more than putting words on paper.  It reaches deep within.  It’s who you ARE.  Furthermore, most writers are not aware of the extraordinarily powerful advantage they have:</p>
<p>IDENTITY:  “I am a writer.”</p>
<p>Very few people on earth know who they are, or what their purpose is.</p>
<p>But you do.</p>
<p>Seize The Day.</p>
<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-20643" alt="Carpe Diem" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/carpe-diem1.jpg" width="600" height="398" /><span style="font-size: xx-small; color: #ffffff;">_</span><strong style="color: #ca343d; line-height: 1.5em;"><strong></strong></strong></p>
<p><strong style="color: #ca343d; line-height: 1.5em;">Are you procrastinating?  Do you write to a schedule?  <strong>Are you afraid of being judged?  </strong>Please do leave a comment.<br />
</strong><strong style="color: #ca343d; line-height: 1.5em;"><span style="font-size: xx-small; color: #ffffff;">_</span></strong></p>
<p><em><img class="size-full wp-image-4260 alignleft" title="Jonathan Gunson" alt="Jonathan Gunson" src="http://bestsellerlabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/jgphoto.jpg" width="120" height="120" /></em><br />
<em><br />
Article written by Jonathan Gunson</em></p>
<p><em>Author / Book Marketing Coach </em></p>
